s.n.
</emphasis>
s.n. (lectotype MA-814634, designated here; isolectotypes MA 814632, 814633).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B00AA1B0D758A36DC4BB7CAEF0BAE793" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="description">
<paragraph id="C13831E94FD4F516E06239969E8CF245" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B34E788C80FF26536071072F68D12EE9" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
Pubescent to densely hirsute herb; stems twining up to 3 m high. Leaves petiolate, 3-8 
<normalizedToken id="9707434E89661832227C038B8953D267" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-4 cm, ovate-deltoid, strongly auriculate, usually large, apex usually obtuse and mucronate, margin undulate to sinuate, base broadly cordate to hastate with midrib area cuneate onto petiole; petioles 7-15 mm. Flowers (1-) 3-7 in compact axillary, pedunculate umbellate cymes; peduncles 1.5-12 cm; bracteoles 2-5 mm, narrowly lanceolate; pedicels 2-12 mm, apparently accrescent after anthesis; outer sepals 6-6.5 
<normalizedToken id="DEAFDC0F6E24C8F2A334D9770BF4C578" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.5-5 cm, elliptic, obtuse or acute; corolla 1.1-1.5 cm long, white to pink, deeply lobed, midpetaline bands brownish, pilose, terminating in a mucro; ovary glabrous; style divided c. 7 mm above base; stigmas 3 mm, more or less included. Capsule glabrous; seeds smooth. [
<bibRefCitation id="B99086157EF9411EA3FF3D54D5288A69" author="O'Donell, CA" journalOrPublisher="Lilloa" pageId="208" pageNumber="209" pagination="87 - 348" refId="B248" refString="O'Donell, CA, 1959. Convolvulaceas argentinas II. Lilloa 29: 87 - 348" title="Convolvulaceas argentinas II." volume="29" year="1959">
<normalizedToken id="75B9E49A544185DFDB55C2FAA3A01171" originalValue="O’Donell">O'Donell</normalizedToken>
1959
</bibRefCitation>
: 271 p. p., 
<bibRefCitation id="B0730119E035C4F03E0E865F1BECA54F" author="Carranza, E" journalOrPublisher="Instituto de Ecologia, Patzcuaro, Michoacan" pageId="200" pageNumber="201" pagination="1 - 107" refId="B77" refString="Carranza, E, 2008. Flora del Bajio y de Regiones Adyacentes. Instituto de Ecologia, Patzcuaro, Michoacan: 1 - 107" title="Flora del Bajio y de Regiones Adyacentes" year="2008">Carranza (2008</bibRefCitation>
: 4ff.)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6C676D046C81D7A14179F3E644C70B96" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="notes">
<paragraph id="57AEAF9218C0E520BD4B07D024272D97" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4601FADFE24611D5C94829FBBAC3A194" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
We recognise two subspecies, which are distinct through most of their range, but intergrade in parts of northern Argentina (
<emphasis id="C8E9710CBB30C4DFEACAE652BA7DEA94" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Morel</emphasis>
5885 from Formosa, 
<emphasis id="FC10ADC8DF2A586BCA365A103E5E1E84" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Schwarz</emphasis>
6391 from Misiones and 
<emphasis id="B4E1E1489669AFD829A06A77156F4AED" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Risso</emphasis>
30 from Santiago de Estero are examples) and in the 
<normalizedToken id="21DBA904067F9F7CAFB78BAF00AC3A0A" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Paulo area of Brazil (
<emphasis id="3D404F6CA2DE0C6DCD70BA555AB36498" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Hoehne</emphasis>
265), mostly at altitudes of around 1000 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
